MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
1. Availability: Martin County Solar Project, LLC (Seller) makes electric energy and capacity available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale. Seller also makes available to any purchaser the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 1:
RTO/ISO Specific
PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM) and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
Third Party Provider
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all sales of energy and capacity by Seller, which are (a) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: The Commission granted Seller in Docket No. ER24-553-000 the following waivers and blanket authorization: (i) waiver of Parts 41, 101 with the exception that waiver of the provisions that apply to hydropower licensees has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects, and 141 of the Commission's regulations, except as to sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and (iii) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities.
7. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northeast region. Seller is a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Central, Northwest, Southeast, Southwest, and Southwest Power Pool regions.
8. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on such date as set by the Commission.

?CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT by and between MARTIN COUNTY SOLAR PROJECT, LLC MARTIN COUNTY II SOLAR PROJECT, LLC, and THREEFORKS ENERGY STORAGE, LLC May 23, 2025
INDEX OF EXHIBITS
Exhibit A Depiction of Switching Facilities (Shared, Solar-Shared, Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS)
Exhibit A-1 Shared Switching Facilities Parcel and Martin II and Martin BESS Easement Areas
Exhibit B Percentage Interest of Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS

CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”) is entered into as of May 23, 2025 (the “Effective Date”), by and between MARTIN COUNTY SOLAR PROJECT, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Martin I”), MARTIN COUNTY II SOLAR PROJECT, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Martin II”), and THREEFORKS ENERGY STORAGE, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Martin BESS”). Each of Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS are referred to herein as a “Party,” and collectively as the “Parties.” RECITALS: A. Martin I, utilizing PJM queue position AF1-130, has constructed and owns and operates a 111 MW solar energy generation facility located in Martin County, Kentucky and associated collection and interconnection lines and substation and related facilities and improvements (the “Martin I Project”). B. Martin II, also utilizing PJM queue position AF1-130, intends to construct, own and operate an approximately 66 MW solar energy generation facility and associated collection lines and related facilities and improvements (the “Martin II Project”) in proximity to the Martin I Project. C. Martin BESS, utilizing PJM queue position AF1-162, intends to construct, own and operate an approximately 100 MW battery energy storage system facility and associated collection lines and related facilities and improvements (the “Martin BESS Project”) in proximity to the Martin I Project and Martin II Project. Together, the Martin I Project, the Martin II Project, and the Martin BESS Project are referred to collectively as the “Projects”, and individually as a “Project”. D. As part of the Martin I Project, Martin I has constructed certain high-voltage facilities, including; (i) a 34 kV collector substation yard with associated equipment and 138 kV substation yard with associated equipment, including main power transformers, circuit breakers, high voltage buswork, metering, conductors and substation control house, batteries, protective relays and communication equipment (collectively, the “Martin I Substation”), and (ii) an approximately 0.09-mile 138 kV interconnection line and associated fiber optic cable and other associated facilities (the “Gen-Tie Line”) that extends from the Martin I Substation terminating structure to the Point of Change of Ownership (as defined below), located at the dead end structure located immediately outside of the Inez 138 kV Substation, thereby connecting the Martin I Project to the transmission system owned by Kentucky Power Company (“KPC”), and the balancing authority area controlled by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (together with any successor authority, “PJM”), with such Martin I Substation and Gen-Tie Line connecting to the Point of Interconnection pursuant to, and as defined in, that certain Interconnection Service Agreement by and among Martin I, KPC, and PJM dated September 14, 2023 (the “Martin ISA”). E. KPC is the Transmission Operator (“TOP”), per the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (“NERC”) TOP standards, of the transmission system at the Point of Interconnection. F. Pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, Martin II intends to and shall have the right to construct new switching facilities within the Martin I Substation (the “Martin II Switching Facilities”) which, when connected to the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities (as defined below), will be used as a point of common coupling of the Martin I Project and the Martin II Project and to electrically tie both Projects into the Gen-Tie Line. The equipment and improvements to be shared between the Martin I Project and the Martin II Project and the facilities for the exclusive use of each of the Martin I Project and Martin II Project are depicted on Exhibit A attached hereto. G. Pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, Martin BESS intends to and shall have the right to construct new switching facilities within the Martin I Substation (the “Martin BESS Switching Facilities” as further described in Recital K) which, when connected to the Shared Facilities (as defined below), will be used as a point of common coupling of the Martin I Project, the Martin II Project, and the Martin BESS Project and to electrically tie all three Projects into the Gen-Tie Line. The equipment and improvements to be shared between the Martin I Project, the Martin II Project, and the Martin BESS Project and the facilities for the exclusive use of each Project are depicted on Exhibit A attached hereto. H. Pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, and in accordance with plans and specifications approved by Martin I, Martin II will directly contract with a construction contractor to cause the expansion of the Martin I Substation high-voltage bus in order to allow electrical connection of the Martin II Switching Facilities (the newly-constructed Martin I Substation high-voltage bus expansion in addition to the existing Martin I Substation high-voltage facilities that are necessary to connect the Martin II Switching Facilities to the Gen-Tie Line are hereafter referred to as the “Solar-Shared Switching Facilities”). The equipment and improvements that comprise the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities are further described and depicted in orange on Exhibit A. The Solar-Shared Switching Facilities shall be located on a parcel of land that will be leased, subleased, or granted by easement or subeasement to Martin I and Martin II as co-tenants pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, as generally depicted on Exhibit A-1 attached hereto (the “Shared Switching Facilities Parcel”). I. Martin II desires to install, own, and operate and will directly contract with a construction contractor to install, a 34.5 kV overhead and/or underground line(s) to connect the Martin II Project to the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities (the “Martin II Collector Line”), a portion of which will be constructed over and across real property leased and/or owned by Martin I as part of the Martin I Project. J. Martin BESS desires to install, own, and operate and will directly contract with a construction contractor to install a 34.5 kV overhead and/or underground line(s) (the “Martin BESS Collector Line”) to connect the Martin BESS to a, 34.5/138kV Main Power Transformer, 138 kV bus work and associated equipment to connect the Martin BESS Project to the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities, a portion of which will be constructed over and across real property leased and/or owned by Martin I as part of the Martin I Project. These facilities are depicted in the color green in Exhibit A. K. Pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, and in accordance with plans and specifications approved by Martin I, Martin BESS will directly contract with a construction contractor to tap the Gen-Tie Line and cause the insertion of a short 138 kV buss extension, starting at the point of common coupling of the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities and Martin BESS Switching Facilities then extending from the point of common coupling to an additional 138 kV breaker and associated equipment, which will then connect to the Gen-Tie Line. (The newly-constructed high-voltage bus expansion, starting at the point of common coupling of the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities and Martin BESS Switching Facilities, plus the additional breaker and associated equipment that couple to the Gen-Tie Line, are hereafter referred to as the “Solar/BESS-Shared Switching Facilities”, and together, as the context may require, with the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities, the “Shared Switching Facilities”). The Solar/BESS-Shared Switching Facilities and Gen-Tie Line are depicted in red in Exhibit A. The Solar/BESS-Shared Switching Facilities shall be located on a portion of the Shared Switching Facilities Parcel that will be leased, subleased, or granted by easement or subeasement to Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS as co-tenants pursuant to the terms of this Agreement, as generally depicted on Exhibit A-1 attached hereto. L. The integration and connection of the Martin II Switching Facilities, Martin BESS Switching Facilities, the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities and the Solar/BESS Shared Switching Facilities will enable the Martin I Project, the Martin II Project and the Martin BESS Project to have shared access to and use of the Gen-Tie Line between the Shared Switching Facilities up to the Point of Change of Ownership (which through the Transmission Owner interconnection facilities connect to the Point of Interconnection), in order to connect thereto pursuant to the Martin ISA and Martin BESS GIA (as applicable), to reflect a shared Gen-Tie Line between Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS as contemplated in this Agreement. M. Upon completion by Martin II of the Martin II Switching Facilities and Martin II Collector Line, Martin I (and Martin BESS, to the extent the Martin BESS Project is constructed prior to the Martin II Project) desires to permit Martin II to have access to and use of the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities, the Solar/BESS Switching Facilities and the Gen-Tie Line upon the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement. Upon completion by Martin BESS of the Martin BESS Switching Facilities and Martin BESS Collector Line, Martin I (and Martin II, to the extent the Martin II Project is constructed prior to the Martin BESS Project) desires to permit Martin BESS to have access to and use of the Solar/BESS-Shared Switching Facilities and the Gen-Tie Line upon the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement. The Gen-Tie Line and the Shared Switching Facilities thereafter will be collectively referred to as the “Shared Facilities”. The Shared Facilities shall not include (i) the portion of the Martin I Substation not part of the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities or Solar/BESS Shared Switching Facilities, (ii) the Martin II Collector Line, (iii) the Martin II Switching Facilities, (iv) the Martin BESS Collector Line, and (v) the Martin BESS Switching Facilities. The Shared Facilities shall, as the context requires, include (x) the Gen-Tie Line and Solar-Shared Switching Facilities with respect to and in the context of the Martin I Project and Martin II Project and as between Martin I and Martin II, and (y) the Gen-Tie Line and Solar/BESS Shared Switching Facilities, with respect to and in the context of the Martin I Project, Martin II Project, and Martin BESS Project and as between Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS. N. Subject to the terms contained herein, the Parties desire for Martin I to own the Martin I Substation and Gen-Tie Line and to co-own with Martin II the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities; Martin II to co-own the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities and for Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS to co-own the Shared Switching Facilities (other than the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities), and for Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS to have joint-use or overlapping easements (as to the Shared Facilities and Shared Switching Facilities Parcel) in order for Martin I and Martin II to jointly use and operate the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities and for Martin I, Martin II, and Martin BESS to jointly use and operate the Shared Facilities (other than the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities, which shall be co-owned only by Martin I and Martin II) from the Shared Switching Facilities Parcel to the Point of Change of Ownership (the “Shared Property Rights”). O. The Parties wish to set forth herein their respective rights and obligations regarding such ownership of the Shared Property Rights and the ownership, access to and use of Shared Facilities, and regarding the joint use, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and alterations to, the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities as between Martin I and Martin II and the Shared Facilities (other than the Solar-Shared Switching Facilities) as between all Parties. P. The Parties also wish to provide for the appointment of a manager of the Shared Facilities in order to provide certain services with respect to the Shared Facilities (the “Manager”) pursuant to an agreement between the Parties and such Manager, with the initial agreement to be executed by and between the Parties and Martin I (the “Initial Manager”) pursuant to a form of manager agreement mutually acceptable to the Parties (the “Manager Agreement”). Q. The Parties desire to set forth herein their respective duties, responsibilities and obligations relating to the co-ownership, use, operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities. AGREEMENT: NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants contained in this Agreement and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is acknowledged, the Parties agree as follows: 1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION 1.1 Definitions. The Parties agree that the methodology for determining such damages set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual damages that would be suffered. “Net Revenue Losses” are defined to be calculated as follows: Net Revenue Loss payments (“NRL Payments”) during any period of time for which they are required hereunder (the “NRL Period”) shall equal the sum of (a) the product of (i) the MWh of electricity that were not produced but would have been produced based on the actual renewable energy measurements during the NRL Period, and (ii) the price at which such un-produced electricity could have been sold and delivered in PJM by the Party receiving such NRL Payment at the Commodity Reference Price for electricity during such NRL Period, and (b) if the Party is eligible to receive the ITCs pursuant to 26 U.S.C. §48, the dollar value for the ITCs that would have been payable to the Party receiving such NRL Payments during the NRL Period, in the case of each of clauses (a) and (b), grossed up on an after-tax basis assuming the highest marginal federal and Commonwealth of Kentucky income tax rates then in effect (and no local, foreign or other income taxes). Further, if the Party is eligible to receive renewable energy credits, including those granted pursuant to law, regulation, certification, markets, trading, off-set, private transaction, renewable portfolio standards, voluntary programs, (“RECs”) and if such Party is not otherwise compensated for RECs as part of subsection (a) above, the Party causing the loss of such RECs shall transfer or cause to be transferred to the Party losing such RECs replacement RECs of equal volume, technology type, state and vintage of the RECs being lost. The term “Commodity Reference Price” means PJM real-time locational marginal price that has cleared at PJM’s pricing node for the Projects which will be established upon interconnection of the Projects during the NRL Period or any successor PJM pricing market that reports prices applicable during the NRL Period at the affected Party’s pricing node for all hours during such NRL Period. 7.12.3.
